    'TECTON Urban Planning and Consultancy', 'Pascoal Mario Costa Guglielmi', 'planejamento@tectonurbanismo.com.br', 'Jardim Apurá - Social Urbanism and Park',
    'IMPLEMENTED', 'APPROVED',
    0.0, 0.0,
    'SECTION_III', 'São Paulo - Brazil', 'Unknown',
    NULL, NULL,
    'The Jardim Apurá project consists in the creation of public spaces providing environmental recuperation in the margins of the Billings Reservoir qualificating leisure, sports and housing areas.', 'The Jardim Apurá Project was developed to reconcile guidelines that ensure environmental preservation, with opening new public spaces and improving local housing conditions. It resulted in an urban park with approximately 30.000m² that promotes sports and leisure activities, as well as the recomposition of the territory and its community through the main goal of land property regularization in its entirety.', 'In 2019, it was developed the “Jardim Apurá” Project. In compliance with the Sustainable Development Goals, it visualized the reduction of social vulnerability. Considering the implementation of essential infrastructure networks in addition with the implementation of the Park and recovery of the Apucás and Guacuri Basins. It was made possible to improve and recover the waters and the terrestrial bioma. 
All of the actions have the main goal of improving social housing quality for those who remain.',
    TRUE,
    'LDP47', 'Pascoal Mario Costa Guglielmi; Letícia R. Guglielmi; Elisabete França; Vanessa Padiá de Souza, Maria Teresa Cardoso Fedeli, Ana Clara Gurgel, Mayra Rodrigues, Fernanda Souza Silva.', NULL, NULL
);

-- Row 65: LDP7
INSERT INTO projects (
    organization_name, contact_person, contact_email, project_name,
    project_status, workflow_status,
    funding_needed, funding_spent,
    uia_region, city, country,
    latitude, longitude,
    brief_description, detailed_description, success_factors,
    gdpr_consent,
    external_code, authors, size_sqm, year_completed
) VALUES (
    'Beijing Jiaotong University, China', 'Xi Pan', 'panxi.thu@gmail.com', 'IUCN-Wuzhiqiao Community-based Environmental Education Centre',
    'IMPLEMENTED', 'APPROVED',
    0.0, 0.0,
    'SECTION_IV', 'Fengning', 'China',
    NULL, NULL,
    'IUCN-Wuzhiqiao Community-based Environmental Education Centre is a public welfare project conducted by a team of university student volunteers. The project is located in a village in northern China named Xiaowopu. The village, as the water source of Beijing, is a site of the project “Mega-cities and their Watersheds: Nature-based Solutions for Sustainable Drinking Water Sources” funded by EU China. Since 2017, over 200 volunteers have worked in this village. Taking “Architecture as Social Process” as the principal idea, the project has built a series of public spaces and facilities including a school, an open-air theatre, a public square, a community kitchen, a bridge, a water-taking facility and barrier-free structures, and provided various social services, such as environmental education, clean energy promotion, medical consultation, smartphone using skill training and craftsmen training, in order to improve the living environment and social vitality of the community, and enhance its sustainable development.', 'As a rural community development project led by architects, the principal idea of this project is "Architecture as a Social Process", which means to establish positive social relationships through public building activities. Just like throwing a stone into calm water, building, as an event, can activate the community and promote its development.

The project is located in Xiaowopu, a village in North China. In 2015, the village was included into EU China’s project “Mega-cities and their Watersheds: Nature-based Solutions for Sustainable Drinking Water Sources” as the water source of Beijing. Our team has been working in this village since 2017, and over 200 university students have served as volunteers for the village. We have built a series of public spaces and facilities, including a school, an open-air theatre, a public square, a community kitchen, a bridge, a water-taking facility and barrier-free structures. And we have also provided various social services, such as environmental education, clean energy promotion, medical consultation, smartphone using skill training and craftsmen training.

The most significant strategy of this project is to apply a series of unique modes of work, which include:

1)	Multi-participation Organization: The villagers and student volunteers, as the most important participants, always work together through the whole process of the project, including planning, design, construction and maintenance. While the village committee and NGO provide financial support and coordination. Everyone contributes, and everyone benefits. 
2)	Sneaking Time in the Busy Year: Working all year-round on the farm, the villagers only have free time for construction in slack seasons. And the students are only available during weekends and holidays. Therefore, the project is divided into different stages, which are embedded and conducted in slack seasons and holidays. In other words, the project is distributed in different periods of the year.
3)	The Interweaving of Construction and Use: Different from the linear working pattern of other building projects, this project applies a rolling pattern, interweaving the construction and use of facilities. Once a new facility is built, the benefit it brings encourages the villagers and volunteers to work harder and better on the next one. Thus, a “compound interest” mode is achieved.

What’s more, various strategies are also used in the design process, including the reordering of spaces, preservation of collective memory, emphasis of ritual space, identity shaping of water source village.

The project has brought significant benefits in three ways:

1)	First, through the provision of public space, facilities and social service, the living condition of the villagers is improved, and the public life of the community is more active.
2)	Second, through the provision of environmental education, awareness of environmental protection in the village has been enhanced.
3)	Third, through the provision of opportunities of social practice for the students, potential experts for rural development in the future are cultivated.', 'The project involves 12 SDGs. SDG6、7、12、13、15 focus on the environment, and are positively correlated with each other. SDG3、4、5、8、10 center around the community members and can be realized through shared means such as education provision and facility building. 

1.	SDGs for the environment
SDG 6：Clean Water and Sanitation
Challenge-The villagers had to take drink water in an unhygienic and unsafe way.
Contribution- The project built a water-taking facility that allows multiple villagers to get water in a hygienic, convenient and safe way.

SDG 7 Affordable and Clean Energy
Challenge- Under the government''s rural revitalization strategy, lots of construction activities were going on and consumed a large amount of energy.
Contribution- The project provided examples for reducing energy consumption in construction, such as renovating existing buildings, designing flexible facilities to meet multiple needs, using solar panels and solar lighting, introducing energy-efficient cookers in the community kitchen.

SDG 12 Sustainable Consumption and Production
Challenge- Chemical and plastic products were widely used in village, but the villagers had no awareness of proper waste disposal.
Contribution- The project encouraged less use of plastic packaging and chemical products harmful to the environment, promoted environmental-friendly alternatives, and built garbage incinerators.

SDG 13 Climate Action 
Challenge- Droughts occurred frequently due to climate change, which increased villagers'' anxiety about farming.
Contribution- The project repaired the open-air theatre for the rain-praying ceremony and relieved the villagers'' anxiety in a cultural way.

SDG 15 Life on Land
Challenge- The biodiversity of the environment was threatened by construction and agricultural activities.
Contribution- The project established natural resource archives and a digital museum for the village, and gave lectures to enhance villagers'' awareness of environmental protection.

2.	SDGs for the community members
SDG 3 Good Health and Well-Being
Challenge-The health knowledge and medical condition of the villagers were poor.
Contribution- Through giving health knowledge lectures and introducing doctor volunteers to serve the village, the situation was improved.

SDG 4 Quality Education
Challenge-Most of the villagers had little access to education after the age of 15 (graduation from junior high school).
Contribution- The project not only provided diverse learning materials for children, but also advocated lifelong learning and offered knowledge and skill training to villagers of all ages.

SDG 5 Gender Equality
Challenge- Due to the traditional conception of genders, women were in a disadvantaged position in the village.
Contribution- The project cultivated women''s organizations through collective activities such as square dancing and cooking, and asked the women to help run the community kitchen and environmental education center, which increased women''s participation in public affairs.

SDG 8 Decent Work and Economic Growth
Challenge- The villagers could only earn low income from agriculture, and lacked other sources of income.
Contribution- The project provided employment opportunities in construction activities, and increased the villagers’ income.

SDG 10 Reduced Inequalities
Challenge- Due to the urban-rural dual structure in China, the rural population, especially the elderly, women and children, were neglected in development.
Contribution- The project encouraged women to participate in public affairs, provided barrier-free facilities for the elderly, and offered learning materials to children.

SDG 11 Sustainable Cities and Communities
Challenge- Due to the loss of young population, the community’s vitality was decreasing.
Contribution- By providing public space, reviving traditional activities, and encouraging young people to return, the community’s sustainability was improved.

3.	SDG 17 Partnerships for the goals
Challenge- The development of the community requires multi-disciplinary collaboration.
Contribution- In addition to young architect volunteers, NGOs were introduced to provide financial support, and volunteers majored in agriculture, medicine, anthropology are organized to work together.',
    TRUE,
    'LDP7', 'Xi Pan, Zhongyuan Liu, Shun Lu, Xinchen Guo', NULL, NULL
);

-- Row 66: LDP16
INSERT INTO projects (
    organization_name, contact_person, contact_email, project_name,
    project_status, workflow_status,
