    'College of Architecture and Urban Planning, Tongji University, Shanghai, P.R.CHINA', 'YI Wenjing', '923086411@qq.com', 'Mending the City- Shanghai Railway Station Metro Station Analysis',
    'IMPLEMENTED', 'SUBMITTED',
    0.0, 0.0,
    'SECTION_IV', 'Shanghai', 'China',
    NULL, NULL,
    'Located in the inner ring of Shanghai, Shanghai Railway Station is the second largest railway station in the city. The train tracks have brought about a great fragmentation of urban space and urban life, while the metro station has to some extent mended the rift and witnessed the rise and fall of the urban environment around Shanghai Railway Station.', 'Built in 1986 on the site of the former Shanghai East Railway Station, Shanghai Railway Station is the second largest railway station in Shanghai, adjacent to the Shanghai Long Distance Passenger Terminal, and together with Shanghai Hongqiao Station and Shanghai South Railway Station, it forms the largest railway hub in the eastern coastal region of China - the Shanghai Railway Hub. From 1995 to 2005, three underground lines and two underground stations were built at Shanghai Railway Station. The opening of the underground has enhanced the connection between intercity and urban transport in Shanghai, and the underground passages between the stations have to a certain extent weakened the fragmentation of urban ground space caused by the railway tracks. The subway, as part of the urban transport construction, is closely related to the tides of development in the surroundings of Shanghai railway stations over the past 30 years.', 'The train tracks passing through the Shanghai Railway Station also divide the city into two parts, creating spatial barriers to movement and, to some extent, leading to a difference in urban life and function between the north and south of the station. The connection of the metro station to the north-south square offers the possibility of sustainable development of the urban environment around the station in terms of infrastructure, and stimulates further consideration of the spatial design of the station-city integration. In addition, the urban development around the railway station is closely linked to the construction of the metro, which flourished in the 1990s but has now become a low-end wholesale and retail cluster with less commercial activity than other urban sub-centres, exploring the possibilities of sustainable consumer development in terms of the current situation and outlook of the metro network and urban connectivity.',
    TRUE,
    'IFF39', 'Shanghai Lab, Tongji University', NULL, NULL
);

-- Row 98: EFP2
INSERT INTO projects (
    organization_name, contact_person, contact_email, project_name,
    project_status, workflow_status,
    funding_needed, funding_spent,
    uia_region, city, country,
    latitude, longitude,
    brief_description, detailed_description, success_factors,
    gdpr_consent,
    external_code, authors, size_sqm, year_completed
) VALUES (
    'CSCAE', 'Primitivo González', 'estudio@primitivogonzalez.com', 'Municipal Archive of San Agustín',
    'IMPLEMENTED', 'SUBMITTED',
    0.0, 0.0,
    'SECTION_I', 'Valladolid', 'Spain',
    NULL, NULL,
    'The church of San Agustin, part of a Monastery, was abandoned and in ruins. However, the ruins were still able to evoke its past. The introduction of a new use within them, the city’s archive, allows a new live to the building.', 'The use of heritage links us to our past, while allowing us to look to the future. The church of San Agustin, part of a Monastery of the Augustinian order, founded at the beginning of the 15th century, was abandoned and in ruins. However, the ruins were still able to evoke its past.  The restoration of the existing ruins together with the introduction of new use through superposed structures, has made possible the recovery of this monument for the City Archive of Valladolid.', 'During the 1960s it was contemplated the demolition of the ruins of the church. However this ruins evoke the past of the building and city, and connect the citizens to its past. The new program introduced in the building, respectful with the existing fabric, shows a resilient infrastructure, that can be adapted again in the future if needed. Furthermore, the project generates an open, friendly and accessible space, bringing the archive institution closer to all citizens.',
    TRUE,
    'EFP2', 'Primitivo González, Gabriel Gallegos', 4303.0, NULL
);

